## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

This code has several constructs that are **broken or removed** in .NET 5+:

### Critical Pitfalls

| Issue | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Works (throws `ThreadAbortException`) | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Wakes blocking calls | Obsolete, unreliable with async |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` | Works but has a **race condition**: multiple `Enqueue` calls can coalesce into one signal, losing items | Same bug, but better primitives exist |
| No graceful shutdown | Relied on `Abort` as fallback | Must use cooperative cancellation |

### Hidden Bug in the Original

If `Enqueue` is called twice before `RunLoop` wakes, `Set()` is called twice but `WaitOne/Reset` only cycles once — the second item stays stuck until a *third* enqueue arrives.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signal no more items
        _cts?.Cancel();                       // cancel if stuck waiting

        var waitTime = timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5);
        if (_processingTask is not null)
            await _processingTask.WaitAsync(waitTime);
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

1. **`Channel<T>` replaces `Queue` + `ManualResetEvent` + `lock`** — thread-safe, no lost signals, backpressure support built-in.

2. **`CancellationToken` replaces `Abort`/`Interrupt`** — cooperative cancellation is the only supported model in modern .NET.

3. **`await foreach` + `ReadAllAsync`** — cleanly drains items and exits when the channel is completed or cancelled.

4. **`IAsyncDisposable`** — proper resource cleanup pattern.

### If `Handle` Must Remain Synchronous

The code above already handles this — `Handle(item)` is called synchronously within the loop. If you need a **fully sync API** (no `async` at all), replace `Channel<T>` with `BlockingCollection<T>`:

```csharp
// Sync-only alternative
private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();

private void RunLoop(CancellationToken ct)
{
    foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(ct))
        Handle(item);
}

public void Stop()
{
    _queue.CompleteAdding();
    _cts?.Cancel();
    _processingTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
}
```

### Migration Checklist

- ✅ Remove all `Thread.Abort()` / `Thread.Interrupt()` calls
- ✅ Replace `ManualResetEvent` signaling with `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>`
- ✅ Add `CancellationToken` for cooperative shutdown
- ✅ Use `Task.Run` instead of raw `Thread` (benefits from ThreadPool)
- ✅ Implement `IAsyncDisposable` for cleanup
